          "body": "God's response to Jeremiah's theodicy question is one of Scripture's most striking pastoral maneuvers: He does not answer the question. He asks a harder one. 'If you have run with footmen and they have tired you out, then how can you compete with horses?' (12:5). The logic is not evasion; it is preparation. Jeremiah is tired from the minor trouble of Anathoth — his own townspeople plotting against him (11:21-23). God's response is that this is the easy terrain. The Jordan's thickets — symbol of Judah's most dangerous lion country — is coming. The betrayal of family will come (12:6). The destruction of Jerusalem will come. The false prophets will come in full force (chapters 27-28). A man who cannot bear Anathoth's footmen will be destroyed by the horses. Howard Hendricks used to note that God rarely answers our questions about suffering — He responds to the questioner. Here He responds to Jeremiah not by explaining the prosperity of the wicked but by preparing the prophet for worse. The pastoral implication is permanent: the theodicy question, unresolved, becomes the school where endurance is built."
