          "title": "God's own lament — the beloved forsaken (12:7-13)",
          "body": "The most theologically startling moment in the chapter is the shift at 12:7. Having challenged Jeremiah to toughen up, God begins to grieve. 'I have forsaken My house, I have abandoned My inheritance; I have given the beloved of My soul into the hand of her enemies' (12:7). Three perfect-tense verbs mark a decision already accomplished — God has done this. The phrase 'beloved of My soul' (*yedidut nafshi*) is intimate to the point of aching. The same root underlies the name Jedidiah ('beloved of Yahweh,' 2 Sam. 12:25, Solomon's throne name). God is not indifferent; He is bereaved. The metaphors escalate: the inheritance has become like a roaring lion against Him (12:8); like a speckled bird of prey being mobbed by other birds (12:9); a vineyard trampled by many shepherds (12:10); a pleasant field turned desolate wilderness (12:10-11). Each image strips away another layer of covenantal relationship. The 'many shepherds' (*ro'im rabbim*, 12:10) are the foreign kings and their armies — the same image Ezekiel 34 will develop extensively. The harvest of thorns in 12:13 is the chapter's most comprehensive judgment-summary: they labored, but under God's fierce anger every effort produced its opposite."
