          "title": "Judgment, compassion, and the inclusion of nations (12:14-17)",
          "body": "The chapter closes with a formally introduced oracle that is among Jeremiah's earliest explicit promises of restoration and the earliest hint of international covenant-inclusion in the book. God announces uprooting for the wicked neighbors who have struck at Israel's inheritance (12:14) — but then, remarkably, He announces uprooting for Judah as well (*I will uproot the house of Judah from among them*, 12:14). Both parties are judged. Then the horizon shifts: 'after I have uprooted them, I will again have compassion' (12:15). The word *racham* — womb-mercy, visceral tenderness — stands alone as the chapter's single greatest theological surprise. After all the devastation imagery of 12:7-13, a single word announces that God's purpose is not permanent annihilation. The nations can be built up in the midst of His people if they learn the ways of His people and swear by His name (12:16). Peter Davids' observation about James applies equally to the wisdom-tradition behind Jeremiah: restoration, when it comes, reverses the direction of the corruption — those who had taught Israel to swear by Baal (12:16) must now learn to swear by Yahweh. The chapter ends where biblical eschatology always tends: judgment is real, judgment is severe, but it is bounded by a compassion that will, in the end, reconstitute what has been scattered. The New Testament's fulfillment of this trajectory is the ingathering of the Gentiles (Romans 11:11-24; Eph. 2:11-13)."
